## ðŸ“‹ Overview
This project documents my hands-on training as a **SOC Analyst**, focusing on attack surface monitoring and intrusion detection using Linux environments (Google Cloud Shell).

## ðŸ” Exercise 1: Port & Service Auditing (Attack Surface)
As a first step in a security audit, I identified the services "listening" for external connections to map the potential attack surface.

**Command executed:**
`ss -tulpn`

### Technical Analysis:
| Column | Technical Meaning | Observation |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Local Address** | IP and Port where the service is listening. | Identified ports on `0.0.0.0` (open to the world). |
| **Peer Address** | Remote address of the connecting client. | Value `*:*` indicates the port is in `LISTEN` state (idle). |
| **State: LISTEN** | The port is open and available. | Port **22 (SSH)** was found active. |

**Security Finding:** High ports (e.g., 8998, 38465) were detected on `127.0.0.1`. Since they are bound to *localhost*, these services are not visible from the internet, complying with system hardening best practices.

